    [
      "p",
      null,
      "Depending on what device you are on, ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "platforms"
      ],
      " can return multiple values. Each possible value is a hierarchy of platforms. For example, on an iPhone, it would return ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "mobile"
      ],
      ", ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "ios"
      ],
      ", and ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "iphone"
      ],
      "."
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "h3",
      {
        "id": "ready-promise-string-"
      },
      " ",
      [
        "a",
        {
          "href": "#ready-promise-string-"
        },
        [
          "code",
          null,
          "ready() => Promise<string>"
        ]
      ],
      " "
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      "Returns a promise when the platform is ready and native functionality can be called. If the app is running from within a web browser, then the promise will resolve when the DOM is ready. When the app is running from an application engine such as Cordova, then the promise will resolve when Cordova triggers the ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "deviceready"
      ],
      " event. The resolved value is the ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "readySource"
      ],
      ", which states the platform that was used."
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      "For example, when Cordova is ready, the resolved ready source is ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "cordova"
      ],
      ". The default ready source value will be ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "dom"
      ],
      ". The ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "readySource"
      ],
      " is useful if different logic should run depending on the platform the app is running from. For example, only Capacitor and Cordova can execute the status bar plugin, so the web should not run status bar plugin logic."
    ],
